A tonne of 'evidence' was adduced in the (instant) trial. However, not all could be considered. A fair and just determination of the issues and a correct judgment require proper evidence and there can only be proper evidence if the issues were clear in the minds of the parties and of the court and evidence was adduced and admitted accordingly [see Saraswatee d/o Arumugan & Anor v Tan Chong & Motors Co Sdn Bhd
[1985] 1 MLJ 327
].

In Common Law, omnia praesumuntur contra spoliatorem , things are presumed against a wrongdoer. Therefore, in a civil proceeding, 'if a man by his own tortious act, withhold the evidence by which the nature of his case would be manifested, every presumption to his disadvantage will be adopted' [1 Smith LC (13th Ed) p 404]. Where a party has the means in his power of rebutting and explaining the evidence adduced against him, if it does not tend to the truth, the omission to do so furnishes a strong inference against him [ A-G v Windsor
24 Beav 679 at p 706
].

Everything is to be presumed against a party who keeps his adversary out of the possession of evidence by taking means of retaining the evidence in his own custody. A similar presumption may also arise when a party does not call witnesses who are within his reach and are acquainted with the facts of the case [ 
Thulai v SA



















 1973 AIR SC 501


;
Virendra v Jagiwan



















 1974 AIR SC 1957


; 
Sooriah v Cotaghery











 2 MIA 113, 125; 
U Po v Edward



















 1934 AIR Rang 139


; 
Trailakhya v Kenaram

















 61 CLJ 551


 ]. When a party failed to call as his witness the principal person involved and who was in a position to give first hand account of the matter in controversy and who could have refuted on oath the allegation on the other side, it is legitimate to draw an adverse inference. The court may draw adverse inference against a party who being in a better position to adduce better evidence deliberately abstain from doing so. Persons omitting to produce their best available evidence cannot take advantage of the abstract doctrine of onus of proof [ 
Md Hussain v Secretary of State



















 AIR 1939 Lah 330


 ].

'One of the most difficult features where wills made by old people are in question is their varying state of mental capacity. At some time, they may be confused while, at others, they are completely lucid. Fluctuant confusion of this nature is particularly characteristic of dementia caused by arterial blockage … Evidence which conclusively shows that within a few days of his testamentary act a person was quite incapable of making a will does not necessarily prove that he was incapable at the time he actually made it. For this reason, the evidence of those present when the deceased gave instructions for his will or at its execution (if they were not merely witnesses called into his presence for a few moments) is of considerable weight. This is particularly so where such persons were unprejudiced and where the court is satisfied that they took pains to assess the mental state of the deceased and where they give evidence of facts and matters which support their assessment. In many cases, the evidence of such lay witnesses has been preferred to medical evidence … It has been said that when a solicitor is drawing up a will for an aged testator or one who has been seriously ill, it should be witnessed or approved by a medical practitioner who ought then to record his examination (and findings) [see Re Simpson, the deceased; Schaniel v Simpson
(1977) 121 SJ 224
]. Other precautions are that if there was an earlier will it should be examined and any proposed alterations should be discussed with the testator … It is recognized that a person who, in general, has lost testamentary capacity by reason of mental illness may have what is termed 'lucid intervals', when the mind has returned temporarily to a sufficiently balanced state … Once it has been proved or admitted that a testator has, general, lost testamentary capacity through mental illness at a date before the purported will, the burden of proving that it was executed during a lucid interval lies on those who so allege …' (Mortimer, Williams and Sunnuck, pp 164-167).

Suspicion must be removed by the person propounding the will (see 
George Lee Chin Nam v Lie Chin Man




















 [1996] 1 CLJ 82


). The degree of suspicion will vary with the circumstances of the case. It may be slight and easily dispelled — eg by proof of a change since the earlier wills [ 
Constable v Tufnell




















 (1833) 4 Hag Ecc 465


 ]. Though, in cases where the vigilance and suspicion of the court are aroused, the burden of proof may be so heavy that it hardly can be removed [ 
Wintle v Nye




















 [1959] 1 WLR 284


 ].

'If a party writes or prepares a will under which he takes a benefit, that is a circumstance that ought generally to excite the suspicion of the court' [ Barry v Butlin
]. 'There is one rule which has been laid down by the courts … and that is that a person who has been instrumental in the framing of a will, and who obtains a bounty by that will, is placed in a different position from ordinary legatees who are not called upon to substantiate the truth and honesty of the transaction as regards their legacies... But there is a further onus on those who take for their own benefit, after being instrumental in preparing or obtaining a will … the onus of showing the righteousness of the transaction' [ Fulton v Andrew
(1875) 7 HL 448
, per Lord Hatherley]. So where a person propounds a will prepared by himself and under which he takes benefit, he must give clear proof that the testator knew and approved of that part under which he takes a benefit [ Hegarty v King
(1880) 5 LR Ir 249
; affd 7 LR Ir 18 CA]. 'This means that, if no evidence is given by the party on whom the burden is cast, the issue must be found against him [ Barry v Butlin
], but if evidence is given on which the court can come to a determinate conclusion the onus need not be considered. On the other hand, if the evidence is so evenly balanced that no determinate conclusion can be reached, the onus becomes the determining factor of the whole case … It rests upon the person who has procured a will under which he takes a large benefit to show that the will does really express the testator's mind and intention [ Brown v Fisher
(1890) 63 LT 465
]' [17 Halsbury's Law of England (4th Ed) para 915].

Where a testator gives instructions in answer to questions, particularly leading questions, the court will require more stringent proof than in other cases that the will embodies the unprompted testamentary intentions of the deceased [ Green v Skipworth
(1809) 1 Phillim 534 at p 538
]. The fact that the deceased has given no instructions for the will requires explanation Middleton v Forbes
(1787) cited in I ngram v Wyatt
(1828) 1 Hag Ecc 384
at p 395
] and so does the fact that the deceased was without independent advice, legal or otherwise, that his relations and friends were kept from him. A radical departure from testamentary dispositions, long adhered to, requires explanation, especially if the person in whose favour the change is made possess great influence and authority with the deceased and originates and conducts the whole transaction [ Marsh v Tyrrell and Harding
(1828) 2 Hag Ecc 84
at p 87
], and such facts may raise strong suspicion that the change was not the result of the free volition of the deceased [ Marsh v Tyrrell
at p 110]. A variety of other circumstances may combine to show that a person has procured a will for his own benefit. Feebleness of body or mind may not be relied on to question the righteousness of the transaction [ Re R the deceased
[1951] P 10 at p 17
].

Undue influence is not bad influence but coercion [ Williams v Goude
(1828) 1 Hag Ecc 577
at pp 581
596
]. Persuasion and advice do not amount to undue influence so long as the free volition of the testator to accept or reject them is not invaded [ Parfitt v Lawless
at p 474]. Appeals to affection, ties of kindred, gratitude for past services, pity for future destitution are legitimate; but not pressure exerted to overpower the volition without convincing the judgment [ Hall v Hall
]. There is no undue influence unless the testator is in such a condition that if he could speak his wishes would say 'this is not my wish but I must do it' [ Baudains & Ors v Richardson & Anor
[1906] AC 169 at p 184
].

Strictly, to upset a will, the undue influence must be shown to have been exercised in relation to the will itself. Where, however, there is evidence that the testator was so far under the influence of persons benefiting from his will that he was not a free agent, the conclusion may be warranted that undue influence was exercised in relation to the will, even if there is no direct evidence [ Boyse v Rossborough
(1857) 6 HLC 2 at p 51
].

The standard of proof, the allegation of fraud in civil proceedings concerns criminal fraud such as conspiring to defraud, misappropriation of money or criminal breach of trust, is the criminal standard of proof beyond a reasonable doubt; where the allegation of fraud is entirely founded on civil fraud and not on criminal conduct or offence, the civil standard is applicable [ Ang Yeok Seng v Yim Yut Kiu (Personal representative of the estate of Chan Weng Sun, the deceased)
[1997] 2 MLJ 45
].

Lim was not sagacious from the start. He knew, even in 1989, that Cheng Bok, Cheng Poon and Cheng Liat were fighting hammers and tongs. He knew that Cheng Poon coveted absolute control of the properties listed in the 1989 deed. He knew that that 1989 deed was not performed by the deceased. He knew that Howard prepared the 1992 wills that would give control of the estate to Cheng Poon and his two sons. He knew that the deceased had just suffered a stroke. Under those circumstances, Lim ought to have approached the 1992 wills, if even wills of the deceased, with circumspection and with a healthy respect for transparency, rebut any accusation, and Lim who had knowledge of the brothers' tussles could not say that an accusation of impropriety was not foreseeable, that the 1992 wills were not wills of the deceased. Surely, vigilance would have been the order of the day, meet and to rebut any future accusation of any impropriety. Yet Lim, a legal practitioner of 34 years' standing in 1992 (see 
Majlis Peguam Legal Directory 1996
) who ought to have known, attested the 1992 wills, the impression he gave, as run of the mill wills. He sought not even a moment alone with the deceased to ascertain if the 1992 wills were indeed wills of the deceased.

Section 111 applies to wills [ Nandalal v Dasarathi
61 CLJ 304
], so it would appear from Sarkar 's proposition at p 1465:

… testamentary dispositions are excepted from the presumption of undue influence which arises in cases of non-testamentary disposition between parties standing in fiduciary or confidential relationship; in the case of wills, the burden of proving undue influence is on the person who alleges it [ 
Boyse v Rossborough











 ]. Section 111 does not, on the face of it, make an exception in favour of wills … But as s 111 speaks of 'a transaction between parties' which implies bilateral documents whereas a will is an unilateral document … an exception may be created in favour of wills … The burden of proving testamentary capacity and execution is on the proponent. When the person benefited by the will is found to be in a position of active confidence towards the testator, there does not appear to be any reason why the general rule of presumption of undue influence should not arise.

Fraud was alleged, but there was no conclusive evidence, even if the 1992 wills were read over to the deceased, that the deceased knew and approved of the contents of the 1992 wills [ 
Guardhouse v Blackburn











; 
Atter v Atkinson











 ]. Any presumption that the deceased knew and approved of the contents of the 1992 wills, assuming that the 1992 wills were read to the deceased or because there was a proper attestation clause, had been rebutted [ 
Garnett-Botfield v Garnett-Botfield











 ] by the clearest of evidence [ 
Gregson v Taylor











 ].

There was strong and unremittingly suspicion that the deceased was deceived into making the 1992 wills by fraud (in the civil sense) or was constrained to make it by undue influence. Contrary to Mr Koh's contention, the changes to the 1990 wills were not consistent with the changes related on 3 August 1992 to Dr Tan who testified that the deceased only informed him of the change of trustees. The fact that the deceased had no independent advice, legal or otherwise, and that his other children were kept away was not satisfactorily explained. The radical departure from the 1990 wills, radical because all changes solely favoured the nuclear family of the person who prepared the 1992 wills which obviously possessed great influence with the deceased, was not explained. The strong suspicion that the radical changes were not the result of the free volition of the deceased [ 
Marsh v Tyrrell











 ] was not removed.

Even if there was no direct evidence of undue influence, there was more than ample evidence that the deceased was so far under the influence of Cheng Poon and his family that a conclusion is warranted that undue influence was exercised in relation to the 1992 wills [ 
Boyse v Rossborough











 ]. The circumstances attending the execution were consistent with its having been procured by undue influence. The circumstances were not consistent with any other hypothesis [ 
Boyse v Rossborough











 ]. The proponents of the 1992 wills failed to show the righteousness of the transaction or that the 1992 wills expressed the true will of the deceased [ 
Finny v Govett











 ]. All said, the circumstances attending the execution were that suspicious that even if undue influence was not proved, it was, the court is not satisfied as to the righteousness of the transaction [ 
Barry v Butlin; Fulton v Andrew; Re Hartley, Hartley v Fuld (Fuld intervening) (No 3)











 ]. Howard who prepared the wills under which he and his family took their extraordinary bounty and assumed all power failed to substantiate the truth, honesty and righteousness of the 1992 wills [ 
Fulton v Andrew











 ]. Howard failed to give clear proof that the deceased knew and approved of that part under which he and his family took their extraordinary benefits [ 
Hegarty v King











 ]. 'This means that … the issue (substantial validity) must be found against (Cheng Poon, Richard and Howard)' [ 
Barry v Butlin











 ]. The 1992 wills purporting to be executed by the deceased have no validity whatsoever and cannot be admitted to probate.

The plaintiffs who put forward the 1990 wills as the true last will of the deceased had to establish that the deceased knew and approved of its contents at the time when he executed it [ 
Barry v Butlin




















 (1838) 2 Moo PC 480


; 
Guardhouse v Blackburn











 ]. That they attempted to establish by proof of testamentary capacity (the evidence of Hamid, Ghazi Ishak, Say Bee, Beng Tatt, Dr Gafoor, Dr Tan and his five certificates) and due execution (the evidence of the two attesting witnesses) from which knowledge and approval by the deceased of the contents of the 1990 wills could be assumed [ 
Barry v Butlin











 ].

Unquestionably, plaintiffs must satisfy the court that the deceased was of sound disposing mind when he executed the 1990 wills. But sanity is presumed until the contrary is shown [ 
Burrows v Burrows











 ] and where the will is rational on the face of it and is shown to be duly executed and if no other evidence is offered, the court will pronounce for it presuming that the testator was mentally competent [ 
Symes v Green











; 
Sutton v Sadler











 ]. Therefore, Tan's certificates deposing to the sound disposing mind of the deceased only augmented the presumption of sanity and mental capacity of the deceased. It was the icing on the plaintiffs' cake. The absence of Dr Tan's certificates could not rebut the presumption of sanity and mental capacity of the deceased when he executed the 1990 wills. For, to rebut the presumption of sanity, there must be proof to the contrary, on the balance of probabilities. Cheng Hum and Grace who alleged unsoundness of mind had to prove it [ 
Dew v Clark and Clark











; 
Wheeler and Batsford v Alderson











 ], and they failed to adduce any proof. Instead, they relied on their learned counsel's powers of persuasion.

Maybe Cheng Hum did have a point when he said that '(his) mother was like my father's walking stick (and) when she died in 1988, he collapsed,' … and that the deceased thereafter was not his usual self but relied on Cheng Poon. The deceased did rely on Cheng Poon — Lim related that Cheng Poon consulted him several times on behalf of the deceased. But more importantly, with regard to the making of the 1990 wills, was there evidence of the 'undue influence constituted by Cheng Poon's influence, Hamid's influence and Cheng Bok/Cheng Liat's influence' that Mr Yeoh so vigorously canvassed? Was there evidence that 'undue influence was exercised in relation to the 1990 wills as to overpower the volition without convincing the judgment of the deceased? [ 
Hall v Hall











 ]. Was there evidence that the deceased was coerced into making the 1990 wills he did not desire? [ 
Wingrove v Wingrove











 ]. And if it was not shown that undue influence had been exercised to the 1990 wills, was it shown that the deceased was so far under the influence of the persons benefiting from the 1990 wills that he was not a free agent and that a conclusion therefore may be warranted that undue influence was exercised in relation to the 1990 wills? [ 
Boyse v Rossborough











 ]. Cheng Hum and Grace, the parties alleging undue influence in the making of the 1990 wills, must prove or show it. Unlike the 1992 wills, they were on their own. They could not just hope to ride on the evidence adduced by the plaintiffs.

All things considered, it must be deduced that the deceased understood and approved the provisions of the 1990 wills. The plaintiffs who propounded the 1990 wills had discharged the burden of showing the righteousness of the transaction and that the document propounded expressed the true last will of the deceased. 'This means that the issue must be found against (Cheng Hum and Grace)' [ 
Barry v Butlin











 ]. This means that the 1990 wills are the true last wills of the deceased and can be admitted to probate.

There was no evidence that Cheng Poon had actively participated in all his sons' activities. But he was the so-called governing trustee, and once he accepted the office of trustee, 'he must discharge its duties, so long as his character of trustee subsists [ Moyle v Moyle
(1831) 2 Russ & M 710
at p 715
]. The law does not recognize any distinction between active and passive trustees, and a trustee will be fully liable to the cestuis que trust for any loss that occurs, where he has left the management of a trust to a co-trustee [ Bahin v Hughes
(1886) 31 Ch D 390
] (see Philip H Pettir at p�272). In the instant case, Cheng Poon's inactivity amounted to his tacit approval of all that was wrecked by his sons and to his dereliction of duty to safeguard the interests of the estate and of the beneficiaries as a whole. He appointed his children, Howard and Gim Chuan, as additional directors without lawful meetings and without consulting the other beneficiaries who had the majority interests. He showed he had no regard whatsoever for any of the other beneficiaries. He would not even answer his accusers/beneficiaries by the giving of his account from the witness box.

Certainly, there was no due and proper administration of the estate. According to Mr Foo, Howard had even lost control of the US estate to a creditor. Truly, Cheng Poon and his sons (even if the 1992 wills are valid wills) had disqualify themselves by their conduct from continuing the office. Their neglect of duty or inaccuracy of conduct, their acts or omissions showed a want of proper capacity to execute the duties, of honesty and of reasonable fidelity, whether they spent much time or not [ Re Duke of Norfolk's Settlement Trusts
[1978] 3 All ER 907
], they took as allowance for their care and trouble which was not allowed [ Robinson v Pett
(1734) 3 P Wms 249
]. Judging by the events from June 1992, it could be fairly said that the estate if left in their hands would probably be loaded and rendered of little value (see Philip H Pettir at 318). They just did not show that they had the interests of the beneficiaries as a whole. All three displayed, and their conduct both before and after the death of the deceased must be considered, that they are not proper persons to look after the interests of the estate and beneficiaries as a whole. Their continuance as executors and trustees would be detrimental to the estate and would further imperiled the interests of the other beneficiaries. The objective test is the due and proper administration of the estate, and in the instant case, there is more than sufficient cause to discharge Cheng Poon and Richard as executors and trustees of the estate.

The objective of an award under this category is to punish the defendants and to display the court's indignant attitude towards the acts committed by the defendants [ Roshairee bin Abd Wahab v Mejar Mustafa bin Omar & Ors
[1997] 2 AMR 2044
]. But before considering any exemplary damages, it must be considered whether the award in mind for compensatory damages would be adequate [ Chong Siew Chiang v Chua Ching Geh
[1995] 1 MLJ 551
].

that probate of the wills dated 24 October 1990, upon their petition, be granted to Cheng Bok and Teik Lim, the remaining executors and trustees, under  O 71 of the 

































Rules of the High Court 1980

